an King, Frederick William II, was a member of the order. Historians have often perceived the Golden and Rosy Cross as having had a conservative, anti-Enlightenment agenda, but this study – drawing on rare German sources – shows that the matter was more complex. The members of the order practiced alchemy and operated a degree system that was later imitated by later orders such as the Golden Dawn. Like the latter, the Golden and Rosy Cross exerted a wide and enduring cultural influence. Both the alchemy of the order and its powerful ritual system are insightfully described in Christopher McIntosh's clear and compelling style.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEnlightenment. 0aRosicrucianszEurope, CentralxHistoryy18th century. 4aHistory : European History. 4aHistory : Intellectual History. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Esotericism and Gnosticism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Mysticism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Spirituality. 7aBODY, MIND & SPIRIT / Hermetism & Rosicrucianism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438435619423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438435619/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles